    <annotation>
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="IT">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Amore che principalmente dee esser fra Cortegiani.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                The love that there should be should principally between courtiers. <!-- CG: I think you'v got one "should" too many! -->
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="IT">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Modestia e grandezza nella Duchessa
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Elisabetta Gonzaga"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                The modesty and grandeur of the Duchess.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="IT">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Le virtu di que[sta] Signora sono abo[n]deuolmente discri[tta] dal Bembo    <!-- CG: The cut off letters are most likely "tte" to agree with "le virtu" -->
                        nel su[o] Dialogo latino, ch[e] di bri[o] della mo[da] del Duca copos[e]    <!-- CG: It took some time to figure this out, but I think it reads "dal Bembo nel suo Dialogo latino, che di lei e della moda del Duca compose" -->
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Elisabetta Gonzaga"/>
                    <person name="Pietro Bembo"/>
                    <person name="Guidobaldo da Montefeltro"/>
                    <book title="De Guido Ubaldo Feretrio"/>    <!-- CG: I looked around for some more info on this dialogue, and it looks like the Italian studies refer to it as "De Urbini ducibus" -->
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                The virtues of this lady are abundantly described in Bembo's Latin dialogue,    <!-- CG: If my above suggestion holds, this would probably become: "The virtues of this lady are abundantly described by Bembo in his Latin dialogue, which he wrote about her and the Duke's style" -->
                which he composed about the Duke's style of wit.  
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
